  "prompt": "What will happen if pilots die and the door is locked?",
  "response": "If both pilots become incapacitated and the cockpit door is locked, the following protocols and procedures are typically in place to address such emergencies:\n\n1. **Cockpit Access**:  \n   - **Emergency Code**: Flight attendants can input a designated emergency code into the cockpit door keypad. This triggers a 30\u201360 second countdown, after which the door unlocks **unless a conscious pilot inside manually overrides it**. If the pilots are unresponsive, the door will open.  \n   - **Backup Measures**: Some aircraft have physical keys or override tools (e.g., axes) stored discreetly for extreme scenarios.\n\n2. **Crew Response**:  \n   - Flight attendants are trained to recognize pilot incapacitation and follow checklists to access the cockpit.  \n   - Once inside, they would attempt to revive the pilots using emergency oxygen and first-aid procedures.\n\n3. **Seeking External Assistance**:  \n   - Air traffic control (ATC) would be contacted via radio. Controllers can guide crew or a qualified passenger (e.g., an off-duty pilot) through emergency procedures.  \n   - Modern aircraft often have **autopilot systems** that can maintain course, and some are equipped with **autoland** technology, enabling automated landings at supported airports.\n\n4. **Passenger Involvement**:  \n   - ATC or crew may ask if there\u2019s a passenger with flying experience (e.g., private pilots or military personnel) to assist. They would follow ATC instructions to manage the descent and landing.\n\n5. **Historical Precedents**:  \n   - While rare, similar incidents (e.g., **2005 Helios Airways Flight 522**) highlight the risks of hypoxia and procedural failures. In 2009, a passenger with flying experience successfully landed a plane in Florida after the pilot fell ill.\n\n**Outcome**: The aircraft would likely attempt an emergency landing, guided by ATC and automated systems. Success depends on crew training, available technology, and external assistance. Modern aviation systems are designed with redundancies to mitigate such critical scenarios.",
